# World History O/X
> Key events and figures in history
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.history.world-history/

World War II ended in 1945. | O | World War II ended in 1945 with the surrender of Germany and then Japan.
The Great Wall is located in China. | O | The Great Wall was built across northern China to defend against invasions.
The first humans landed on the Moon in 1969. | O | Apollo 11 carried the first humans to walk on the Moon in 1969.
The ancient Egyptians built the pyramids at Giza. | O | The pyramids at Giza were built by the ancient Egyptians as tombs for their pharaohs.
The Roman Empire was centered on the Mediterranean Sea. | O | At its height, the Roman Empire surrounded and controlled the Mediterranean region.
Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492. | O | In 1492, Columbus crossed the Atlantic and reached islands in the Americas.
World War I began in 1950. | X | World War I began in 1914; 1950 was the start of the Korean War.
The pyramids of Egypt were built by the ancient Romans. | X | The pyramids were built by the ancient Egyptians, long before the Roman Empire existed.
Napoleon was an emperor of England. | X | Napoleon was an emperor of France, and he fought against Britain.
The printing press with movable type in Europe was invented by Shakespeare. | X | In Europe, Johannes Gutenberg is credited with the movable-type printing press; Shakespeare was a playwright.
The Berlin Wall fell in 1789. | X | The Berlin Wall fell in 1989. 1789 was the start of the French Revolution.
Ancient Greece is famous for building the Taj Mahal. | X | The Taj Mahal was built in India under the Mughal Empire, not in ancient Greece.
During World War II, Winston Churchill was the prime minister of France. | X | Churchill was the prime minister of the United Kingdom, leading Britain through most of World War II.
The Titanic sank in 1912. | O | The Titanic struck an iceberg and sank on its first voyage across the Atlantic in April 1912.
Cleopatra was a queen of ancient Egypt. | O | Cleopatra VII was the last active ruler of ancient Egypt's Ptolemaic dynasty.
Julius Caesar was the first emperor of Rome. | X | Caesar was a Roman general and dictator but never emperor; his heir Augustus became Rome's first emperor.
The Colosseum in Rome was used for gladiator contests. | O | The Colosseum was a huge amphitheatre where ancient Romans watched gladiator fights and other public spectacles.
Machu Picchu was built by the Aztec Empire. | X | Machu Picchu was built by the Inca in the mountains of Peru; the Aztec Empire was in Mexico.
The Hundred Years' War lasted exactly one hundred years. | X | The Hundred Years' War between England and France actually lasted 116 years, from 1337 to 1453.
The Vikings came from Scandinavia. | O | The Vikings were seafarers from Scandinavia, the region of modern Denmark, Norway, and Sweden, who raided and traded across Europe.
Genghis Khan founded the Mongol Empire. | O | Genghis Khan united the Mongol tribes around 1206 and founded an empire that became the largest contiguous land empire in history.
Marie Antoinette was a queen of Spain. | X | Marie Antoinette was the queen of France, married to Louis XVI, and was executed during the French Revolution.
The Renaissance began in Italy. | O | The Renaissance, a rebirth of art and learning, began in Italian cities like Florence in the 14th century before spreading across Europe.
The Industrial Revolution began in Germany. | X | The Industrial Revolution began in Britain in the late 18th century, powered by steam engines and textile factories.
The United States Declaration of Independence was adopted in 1776. | O | The Declaration of Independence was adopted on July 4, 1776, announcing the American colonies' separation from Britain.
Joan of Arc was an English military leader. | X | Joan of Arc was a French heroine who led French forces against England during the Hundred Years' War.
The Wright brothers made the first powered airplane flight in 1953. | X | The Wright brothers first flew a powered airplane in 1903 at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina, fifty years earlier.
Abraham Lincoln was president of the United States during the American Civil War. | O | Lincoln led the Union through the Civil War (1861-1865) and issued the Emancipation Proclamation against slavery.
The Cold War was mainly a rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union. | O | After World War II, the United States and the Soviet Union competed for global influence for decades without fighting each other directly.
The United States gained its independence from France. | X | The American colonies won independence from Britain; France actually helped the Americans in that war.
The Soviet Union collapsed in 1961. | X | The Soviet Union was dissolved in 1991; 1961 was the year the Berlin Wall was built.
The ancient Olympic Games were held in Greece. | O | The ancient Olympics were held at Olympia in Greece every four years in honor of the god Zeus.
The Aztec Empire was located in what is now Mexico. | O | The Aztec Empire flourished in central Mexico, with its capital Tenochtitlan on the site of today's Mexico City.
Alexander the Great was a king of Persia. | X | Alexander was the king of Macedonia in Greece; he conquered the Persian Empire rather than ruling it as a Persian king.
Nelson Mandela became South Africa's first Black president in 1994. | O | After 27 years in prison, Mandela was elected president in South Africa's first fully democratic election in 1994.
The samurai were warriors of ancient China. | X | The samurai were the warrior class of Japan, serving lords under a strict code of honor for centuries.
